      <profileDesc>
         <abstract>
            <p>The synaxarion, Sǝnkǝssār in Ethiopia, is a liturgical work containing commemorative notices of persons, events or feasts for each day of the year. The Ethiopic
            Sǝnkǝssār war translated from the Copto-Arabic synaxarion at least twice (<ref type="work" corresp="LIT4032SenkessarS"/>
            and <ref type="work" corresp="LIT4033Senkessar"/>), each translation depending on a different Arabic Vorlage. The translation was extensively revised in Ethiopia, 
            both regarding content and language (<ref type="work" corresp="LIT4968SenkessarSec"/>).</p>
         </abstract>
         <creation notBefore="1375" notAfter="1425" corresp="#Psttanthony">The translation  <ref type="work" corresp="LIT4032SenkessarS"/> was carried out around
               <date>1400</date> by <persName ref="PRS8743Semon"/>, a monk of <placeName ref="INS0320DAA" xml:id="Psttanthony"/>, according to the colophon
            of the translation present in <ref type="mss" corresp="BNFabb66A"/>.</creation>
         <creation notBefore="1375" notAfter="1400">The translation <ref type="work" corresp="LIT4033Senkessar"/> goes probably also back to the end of the 14th
            century.</creation>
    
